  "prompt": "What precautions were taken with Apollo 10 to ensure it did not land on the moon?",
  "response": "During the Apollo 10 mission in May 1969, NASA intentionally ensured that the lunar module (LM) would not land on the moon. The mission was essentially a \"dress rehearsal\" for the Apollo 11 moon landing, and its purpose was to test all procedures and components for a potential lunar landing without actually touching down.\n\nTo prevent landing, NASA deliberately left just enough fuel in the lunar module for the mission's specific test objectives. The LM was intentionally configured with a limited fuel supply that would make a landing impossible. The crew (Thomas Stafford, John Young, and Eugene Cernan) were instructed to fly the LM to within approximately 50,000 feet of the lunar surface to test navigation, landing procedures, and the lunar module's performance, but were specifically prohibited from attempting a landing.\n\nThis approach allowed NASA to comprehensively test the lunar landing procedures and equipment without the risk of an unplanned landing, serving as a critical final preparation step before the Apollo 11 mission's actual lunar landing in July 1969.",
